introduction.p:

Consider two vectors \vec A and \vec B with an angle \theta between them, as illustrated in . The result of a vector or cross product between them, denoted by   \vec A \times \vec B, has the magnitude and direction (illustrated in ) given by


	 \amp \text{Magnitude } = A B \sin\theta, \text{ and} 
	 \amp \text{Direction: Use Right Hand Rule.}

solution.p:
(b)

				\amp\text{Magnitude = } ILB\sin\theta=10\times 0.2\times 1.5\times \sin\, 90^{\circ} = 3\,\text{A.m.T} 
				\amp\text{Direction; Using right hand rule we get due East. }  

			The unit of force came out to be \text{A.m.T} , which actually turns out to be same as  \text{N} .
